notes.note:
Customer's lawyer/mom (I think) challenged the Do it your self and authorized dealer lines.
My reply:
Sorry for the delay in responding.
The contract does not state what constitutes an authorized repairer. It instructs the warranty holder to call our claims line for a referral to an authorized repairer.
Since the oil change cannot be proven, we must assume it was not performed and this would directly affect the condition of the engine. The fact that the vehicle was in a remote area does not excuse the requirement of having the oil change done by an authorized repairer. The oil and filter were purchased somewhere. I'm sure the oil change could have been done in that location.
The line "may refuse or cancel this Warranty contract", leaves it to our discretion whether the warranty is cancelled. For instance, if a customer had a covered alternator claim but had not performed their maintenance, CGW would likely not cancel their warranty coverage for this.
The key is that the warranty holder is required to call. They should not make assumptions. A phone call to our office for direction likely would have averted this situation.
Our requirements for maintenance are no different than those of the manufacturer's. The manufacturer would not accept do-it-yourself oil changes and neither does Canada General.

I'm sorry we cannot be of assistance.

Respectfully,
Adam Halko
Claims Manager
